--- title: "Family Feud - NYT Crossword Edition" author: "Simon Heitin" date: "2022-09-28" format: html: self-contained: true code-fold: true code-summary: "Show the code" execute: warning: false message: false freeze: auto categories: [tidytuesday, code] --- If there's one thing that unites my family, it's a love of food[^1]. If there are two things that unite my family, they are a love of food and a love of puzzles. So, when I saw that [tidytuesday](https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday) had wrangled [a set of crossword clues and answers](https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/blob/master/data/2022/2022-04-19/readme.md), I knew what I had to do. [^1]: this post is not about about food but maybe the next one should be I emailed my family members and asked them to submit one guess as to what they thought was the most common 4-letter crossword answer. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(tidyverse) library(lubridate) path <- 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2022/2022-04-19/times.csv' times <- read_csv(path) times_clean <- times %>% mutate(answer = str_remove_all(answer, " "), answer_len = nchar(answer)) %>% filter(!is.na(puzzle_date)) #these are the guesses. I provided a pseudonym for each family member to keep # things friendly. https://babynames.com/names/random-name-generator.php was a # big help fam_responses_anon <- data.frame( stringsAsFactors = FALSE, answer = c("ANTE","ERRS","HOME", "IDEA","DERN","BEAU","SETS","EONS","ERAS","TIME", "WELL","WHAT","ACRE","STAG","ARIL", "LAST", "CLAM", "FOUR", "WILL", "BALL"), pseudonym = c("Keona","Gordian","Zai", "Makaila","Olof","Quintana","Selene","Ceron", "Harrison","Mignonette","Tua","Alysha","Ziva", "Maddox","Mervin", "Ultimate Warrior", "Janet", "Tarzan", "Spock", "Sally") ) # get the number of occurrences for each 4-letter word answers_ordered <- times_clean %>% filter(answer_len == 4) %>% count(answer, name = "n_appearances") %>% arrange(desc(n_appearances)) # to calculate percentiles, we need to answers_pctile <- answers_ordered %>% count(n_appearances, name = "n_answers") %>% arrange(desc(n_appearances)) %>% mutate(num_better_answers = lag(cumsum(n_answers), default = 0), pct_better_answers = num_better_answers / sum(n_answers), pctile = 1-pct_better_answers) %>% right_join(answers_ordered, by = "n_appearances") # now just get the answers from my family family_answers_pctile <- answers_pctile %>% right_join(fam_responses_anon, by = "answer") %>% mutate(pctile = replace_na(pctile, 0), num_better_answers = replace_na(num_better_answers, 2000)) ``` ::: ## Bum Bum Ba Da Buuuuum - Results The plot below shows the results of our challenge. The y-axis is the percentile for how common each 4-letter word is. So, if a word is in the 90th percentile, then it is more common than 90% of all 4-letter words (that appeared in at least one crossword puzzle). ::: {.cell .fig-cap-location-bottom} ```{.r .cell-code} library(ggrepel) library(scales) family_answers_pctile %>% ggplot(aes(y = pctile)) + geom_vline(xintercept = 0) + geom_point(aes(x = 0), alpha = .3, stroke = 0) + # stat_ecdf() + geom_label_repel(aes(label = answer, x = 0), max.overlaps = 20, fill = "light blue") + scale_y_continuous(labels = label_percent(), limits = c(0,1)) + theme_light() + theme(axis.text.x=element_blank(), axis.ticks=element_blank(), axis.title.x=element_blank(), panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank()) + labs(y = "Answer Percentile") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![Family Guesses and Their Resulting Percentiles](index_files/figure-html/plot_results-1.png){fig-alt='a scatterplot with a single vertical line. The x-value is 0 for each point and the y value corresponds to the percentile of each word. Each word itself is labeled. The top two words are \'WELL\' and \'STAG\'.' width=384} ::: ::: A keen eye will note that the top answer, "WELL", is at the 100th Percentile. That's right, one family member chose the absolute most common 4-letter crossword clue! It's no wonder that this is also the person who made a living out of playing poker through serious study and computer simulation. ## Try For Yourself Type an answer in ALL CAPS in the text box in the first column below. This is limited to 4-letter answers. The time range is 2012-12-27 to 2021-09-12. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(reactable) answers_pctile %>% mutate(percentile = scales::percent(pctile, accuracy = .01)) %>% select(`Answer` = answer, `Answer Percentile` = percentile, `No. of Puzzles in Which Answer Appeared` = n_appearances) %>% reactable::reactable(filterable = TRUE, defaultPageSize = 1) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
